  <exercise xml:id="empty-3">
    <statement>
      <p>Fix the code below so that it creates a vector with 5 elements initialized to 1, and changes
                    the third element of that vector to a 2.</p>
    </statement>
    <program interactive="activecode" line-numbers="yes" xml:id="vectors_a1q_editor">
      <input><![CDATA[
#include <iostream>


using namespace std;

int main() {
    vector<int> nums (5) = 1;
    nums[3] = 2;
}
        ]]></input>
    </program>
    <solution>


    
                Below is one way to fix the program.  You must always include the &lt;vector&gt; header when
                    dealing with vectors.  Furthermore, to initialize a vector's elements to a certain value, you
                    must include that value as a second argument to the size.  Finally, vectors are zero-indexed.

    
    <program xml:id="vectors_a1a_editor" line-numbers="yes"><input><![CDATA[
#include <iostream>
#include <vector>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    vector<int> nums (5, 1);
    nums[2] = 2;
}
        ]]></input></program>

            

