  <exercise xml:id="empty-6">
    <statement>
      <p>Write a function called <c>has_char</c> that returns a boolean of whether every string in the
                    vector <c>vec</c> contains the character <c>let</c>.  It should return true if all strings contain the <c>let</c>.</p>
    </statement>
    <program interactive="activecode" line-numbers="yes" xml:id="vectors_a7q_editor">
      <input><![CDATA[
#include <iostream>
#include <vector>
using namespace std;
        ]]></input>
    </program>
    <solution>


    
                Below is one way to finish the program.  We loop through the vector, and we loop through each string
                    inside it.  If the string has the character, it is added to count.  We then check whether count
                    is equal to the number of elements in vec and return a boolean.

    
    <program xml:id="vectors_a7a_editor" line-numbers="yes"><input><![CDATA[
#include <iostream>
#include <vector>
using namespace std;


int has_char(const vector<string>& vec, char let) {
    int count = 0;
    for (size_t i = 0; i < vec.size(); i++) {
        for (size_t c = 0; c < vec[i].size(); c++) {
            if (vec[i][c] == let) {
                count++;
            }
        }
    }
    if (count == vec.size()) {
        return true;
    }
    return false;
}
        ]]></input></program>

            

